S186: user-directed "swarm the swarm" evolution replay executed across F-EVO2/F-EVO3/F-EVO4 (`experiments/evolution/f-evo2-contamination-s186-swarm-the-swarm.json`, `experiments/evolution/f-evo2-retention-s186-swarm-the-swarm.json`, `experiments/evolution/f-evo3-protocol-cadence-s186-swarm-the-swarm.json`, `experiments/evolution/f-evo4-multibranch-s186-swarm-the-swarm.json`). Actual: contamination improved from `0.5184` to `0.4784` (MEDIUM, ready/running `1.0`), cadence couplings stayed directionally stable (mutation-overhead `+0.3033`, mutation-destabilization `+0.4554`), and multibranch verdict remained full pass (`verdict_strength=1.0`, overall score `0.6989`). S186: floor-`0.3333` coordinator slot-1 operations execution completed via F-OPS3 queue-aging replays (`coordination+verification` check modes) with artifacts `experiments/operations-research/f-ops3-queue-aging-s186-fullhistory-rerun.json` and `experiments/operations-research/f-ops3-queue-aging-s186-synthetic-rerun.json` (using synthetic backlog slice file `experiments/operations-research/f-ops3-queue-aging-s186-synthetic-lanes.md`). Expectation: explicit backlog-slice injection should separate queue-aging from recency-bias so slot policy can progress beyond tie/null. Actual: live replay remains narrow (`ready_session_min=184`, `job_count=20`) and effectively tie (`score=0.9` both), while synthetic backlog replay separates policies (`job_count=26`, ready window `180..186`) but favors `recency_bias` (`0.4038` vs `-0.5077`) because naive queue-aging induces high `global_delay_rate=1.0` and `mean_positive_shift=2.0` despite stale-unresolved improvement (`0.0` vs `0.2308`). Diff: slot-1 produced actionable F-OPS3 signal (aging policy needs guardrails for global-delay/shift, not just stale reduction); coordinator can advance to slot-2 information-science.

S186: F-OPS2 realized guard-vs-unguarded comparison landed via `tools/f_ops2_guard_comparison.py` with regression coverage (`tools/test_f_ops2_guard_comparison.py`, 3/3) and artifact `experiments/operations-research/f-ops2-guard-vs-unguarded-s186.json`. Check mode `coordination`; expectation was to close the open F-OPS2 follow-up by measuring guarded vs unguarded plans against observed lane pickup/collision/blocked churn instead of scheduler-only projections. Actual: comparator reads both artifacts + lane history and reports guarded preference on normalized risk signals (`collision_keyword_rate_per_row 0.0797 vs 0.1429`, blocked-transition rate parity `0.0`), but with pickup-rate regression (`0.7273 vs 1.0`). Diff: guarded profile remains the safer live default, but pickup recovery is now the explicit next optimization target.

Actual: strict adoption remained `18/172` and lag/stale stayed parity (`0.0` / `0.0`), while churn deltas dropped from `updates/lane +7.3015` and lifecycle-density `+5.1587` to `+0.9481` and `-0.1429` (`suppressed_row_count=129`). Diff: no-op suppression materially improves F-GAM3 signal quality; next leverage is a post-`S187` holdout rerun for matured strict-cohort viability.
